    <title>Combined summary - Against Allowing Quantum Recovery of Bitcoin</title>
    <updated>2025-09-22T12:29:51.940951+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://gnusha.org/pi/bitcoindev/CADL_X_cF=UKVa7CitXReMq8nA_4RadCF==kU4YG+0GYN97P6hQ@mail.gmail.com/T/#maa28d9da6af644d2c597d7bc4b8f33893b8d14d1" rel="alternate"/>
    <published>2025-08-09 19:53:00+00:00</published>
    <summary>The discussion around the potential threat of quantum computing to Bitcoin is multifaceted and encompasses various scenarios ranging from quantum computers never becoming a practical threat to suddenly materializing and posing an immediate risk. The crucial question that arises in this context is whether to leave quantum-vulnerable funds open to be swept by anyone with a powerful quantum computer or to permanently lock these funds, essentially &quot;burning&quot; them to keep them out of reach. This debate touches on fundamental properties of Bitcoin, including censorship resistance, forward compatibility, and conservatism.
One of the core principles at stake is encapsulated in the popular saying, &quot;Not your keys, not your coins,&quot; highlighting the importance of private key security in the cryptocurrency realm. A quantum-capable entity would have the ability to break this foundational principle by potentially reverse-engineering private keys, thus threatening the very essence of what makes Bitcoin secure.
Alarmingly, it's not just the long-forgotten Satoshi-era coins that are at risk; active wallets, including those of major exchanges and entities holding large amounts of Bitcoin, could also become targets. The introduction of a quantum-safe signature scheme seems imperative for the survival and security of Bitcoin, prompting a need for early adoption among wallet holders.
The ethical dilemma surrounding this issue is complex, weighing the harm of potentially freezing users' funds against the broader systemic risk posed by quantum attacks. Such attacks could lead to significant economic disruption, wealth redistribution, and erosion of trust in Bitcoin. It raises questions about property rights, fairness, and the responsibility of the Bitcoin community to protect its ecosystem without undermining its decentralized ethos.
Given these considerations, there appears to be a strong case for proactive measures, such as implementing post-quantum cryptography schemes and possibly considering the phased deactivation of older, vulnerable outputs. This approach would aim to safeguard Bitcoin's integrity while minimizing the impact on individual users and the market at large.
In summary, the quantum computing debate within the Bitcoin community underscores the need for a thoughtful, coordinated response that balances security enhancements with respect for the fundamental principles that underpin the cryptocurrency. As the technology landscape evolves, the Bitcoin protocol and its users must also adapt to ensure the longevity and resilience of the network.</summary>
